  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

Through the Gapminder dataset, I will be exploring the relationship between the % of total roads paved and a few other parameters of interest, such as the Human Development Index (HDI), on a cross-country level.

I will only be exploring these variables through descriptive analysis, mainly through plot visualisations. As such, anything other than the mere observation of trends and patterns is beyond the goal of this exercise.

These are my research questions: 1) Is there a relationship between a country's % of total roads paved and its HDI?

  • HDI is a composite, summary measurement of human development that takes three dimensions into account: life expectancy, education, and standard of living

2) What are some of the characteristics of countries with low % of total roads paved but high HDI scores, and vice versa? Parameters used here are GDP and Democracy Index.

Now, let's look at the relationship between % total roads paved and HDI scores in 2009 in a scatter plot diagram.

Since I will be plotting several scatter plots throughout this exercise, I will define a function for it.

In [22]:
def plot_scatter(x_series, 
                 y_series, 
                 title, 
                 x_title, 
                 y_title):
    """Plot scatter plot"""
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
    plt.scatter(x_series, y_series)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=15, pad=20)
    plt.xlabel(x_title, fontsize=15)
    plt.ylabel(y_title, fontsize=15)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=12);

Generally, we can see a positive correlation between both these variables, suggesting that as the total number of roads paved in a country increases, the country's HDI score increases too!

There is however, an obvious outlier in the chart - right at the bottom.

When we look at the scatter plot, especially if we view it in a 2x2 quadrant diagram, we see that some countries with low % of total roads paved (< 50%) still manage to score high HDIs (> 0.5), whereas some countries with high % of total roads paved (> 50%) have low HDIs (< 0.5).

Research Question 2:¶

What are some of the characteristics of countries with low % of total roads paved but high HDI scores, and vice versa?

As described in this World Bank study, the notion put forth was that improved roads led to better socio-economic outcomes for people who particularly reside in rural communities.

To some degree or another, better socio-economic outcomes are necessarily associated with higher education, health, and economic opportunities - all of which may be simplistically summarised in the HDI scores.

And indeed, the scatter plot above does show me a positive correlation between % of total roads paved and HDI scores.

That said, I see countries defying this linear trend, as some nations with much of its roads paved (> 50%) scored low HDIs (< 0.5), while others with less of its roads paved (< 50%) scored high HDIs (> 0.5).

In this regard, why do some countries perform surprisingly better, whereas some perform surprisingly worse?

Of course, I am taking an over-simplified view that the total roads paved in a country is the primary indicator of a populations' state of well-being (it is more complex than that).

Nevertheless, let's throw in some other indicators to see if there exist any patterns or characteristics of countries that either ride with or against the general trend of positively correlated relationship between % of total roads paved and HDI scores in 2009.

Let's first look at the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of the countries, which I take it to be a general proxy of a nation's economic wealth.

Next, I will group the countries into four categories for comparison sake:

  • Countries with high % of total roads paved and high HDI scores (upper right quadrant);
  • Countries with high % of total roads paved but low HDI scores (bottom right quadrant);
  • Countries with low % of total roads paved and low HDI scores (bottom left quadrant); and

In [35]:
def plot_boxplot(quadrant_group_dict,
                 title,
                 x_title,
                 y_title):
    """Plot boxplot for each quagdrant group"""
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
    plt.boxplot(quadrant_group_dict.values())
    plt.title(title, fontsize=15, pad=20)
    plt.xlabel(x_title, fontsize=15)
    plt.ylabel(y_title, fontsize=15)
    plt.xticks([1, 2, 3],['High % Roads Paved, High HDI','Low % Roads Paved, High HDI','Low % Roads Paved, Low HDI'],
               fontsize=12)
    plt.yticks(fontsize=12);

Here, we see that there are many more outlier countries with very high GDP levels in countries with higher HDIs, suggesting an at least, somewhat positive correlation between GDP and HDI. I say somewhat because out of the 177 countries, we only see a handful of outliers. Meaning, a country's GDP would not be the strongest predictor either of a country's HDI.

Secondly, we do also see major overlaps in the boxplots between the three groups, suggesting that a country's GDP may not play a significant role in determining how much of its total roads are paved either.

These observations are confirmed in the scatter plots below.

Let's explore another indicator: Democracy index - expresses the quality of democracies as a number between 0 to 100 %. It is based on 60 different parameters that are related to a country's democratic nature, such as voter participation, perception of human rights protection, and freedom to form organizations and parties.

Limitations¶

  1. Without conducting any in-depth statistical tests to study the relationships between the various indicators as above, it is difficult to ascertain any conclusive results, other than what the visualisations have shown us - in that a country's GDP may not be a good predictor of a country's % of total roads paved, as well as its HDI score. However, secondly, while a country's democratic index may similarly not be a good predictor of a country's % of total roads paved, it does seem to correlate positively with a country's HDI score.

  2. While correlations may be observed in the above graphs, correlation does not imply causation, not when merely exploratory descriptive analysis (EDA) was carried out.

Conclusions¶

Circling back to my research questions, there is a positive correlation between a country's HDI score and its % of total roads paved, but among countries that have high HDI scores in spite of low % of roads paved, their GDPs and democratic indexes do not seem to play important roles in attributing these countries with low % of roads paved with high HDI scores.
